sentences: Francisco Aguabella (October 10, 1925 – May 7, 2010) was an Afro-Cuban  percussionist whose career spanned folk, jazz, and  dance bands.
The first thing you hear when you wake up in the morning is the drums.
In the 1950s, he left Cuba to perform with Katherine Dunham in the Shelley Winters film Mambo filmed in Italy.
He immigrated to the United States in 1953 and performed and toured with Peggy Lee for the next seven years.

He is featured in the 1995 documentary Sworn to the Drum by filmmaker Les Blank, and is featured in a documentary titled Aguabella currently in production, directed by actor/filmmaker Orestes Matacena (The Mask, Bitter Sugar).

Francisco received numerous awards including a 1992 National Heritage Fellowship from the National Endowment for the Arts, the Durfee Foundation's Master Musicians' Fellowship, and recognition by the Los Angeles County Arts Commission.
